        "date": "2026-07-19",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-19T11:52:24.464Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz remains under acute operational stress, with the Crisis Pressure index sitting in the extreme band this morning, even as both state and forecast composites show easing over the past 24 hours. That divergence is significant: the 30-day Escalation Forecast holds in the elevated band, meaning analysts see sustained but moderating forward risk, while current conditions remain more severe than the outlook implies. Physical transit data underlines the pressure: PortWatch's most recent published day, 2026-07-12, logged 10 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88 per day, and physical transit deviation is the top contributor to the state composite. Separately, a scraper-derived 24-hour arrivals count at Gulf ports reached 602 vessels, reflecting a different methodology and scope from the PortWatch corridor figure. As of this morning, 466 vessels were anchored or stopped in the region. The Brent quote is unchanged at $88.10 since the prior brief on 2026-07-18; no new price print has been produced, so no inference about market sentiment should be drawn from that figure. The headline development of the past six hours is the IRGC Aerospace Force's destruction of a US MQ-9 drone over Ahvaz, per Iranian state media, using what authorities described as a new advanced air defense system. That intercept follows US strikes on Iran reported by gCaptain, launched after two American service members were killed in Jordan, and Iranian state media's condemnation of a US attack on Chabahar Port. Iranian state media also reported two vessels suffered accidents after attempting an unauthorized Hormuz transit route, with two additional ships abandoning passage following IRGC warnings. Sixteen indexed events were logged in the past 24 hours.",
        "transitsToday": 10
